<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<title>@HI{{sou desu}}</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{sou desu}}" grammar="@HI{{sou desu}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{sou desu}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @EM{{@HI{{sou desu}}}}
<li> @EM{{@HI{{sou jaarimasenn}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{sou desu}}}} can be used to reply to a noun sentence in the affirmative.
To anser in the negative, use @EM{{@HI{{sou jaarimasenn}}}}. An equivalent negative response
would be to use @KJ{{difference}}@HI{{imasu}}.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{soreha@KJ{{book}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{hai, sou desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this a book?      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yes it is.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{soreha@KJ{{hon}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{iie, sou jaarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this a book?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No it isn't.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{soreha@KJ{{hon}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{iie, @KJ{{chiga}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this a book?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No, you are mistaken.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

